CONFIG = src/config/hero.lattice.dsl
PRIMARY_VALIDATORS = src/include/hero/lattice_hero/hero_lattice.h

DESCRIPTION
  Lattice Hero v0 is a read-only MCP/direct-tool surface for target readiness
  and lineage inspection. It scans runtime job artifacts into an in-memory
  exposure ledger, evaluates hero.lattice.targets.dsl, and can inspect
  checkpoint exposure closures.

KEYS
  protocol_layer
    Allowed: STDIO, HTTPS/SSE.
    Current runtime supports STDIO only. HTTPS/SSE fails fast.

  default_config_path
    Global .config used to find Hero-owned Lattice target and split DSL paths.

  lattice_targets_dsl_bnf_path
    Grammar for hero.lattice.targets.dsl.

  lattice_targets_dsl_path
    Active Lattice target catalog. This is a Hero-owned config pointer under
    [HERO], not a Kikijyeba environment/protocol pointer.

  lattice_splits_dsl_bnf_path
    Grammar for hero.lattice.splits.dsl.

  lattice_splits_dsl_path
    Active Lattice split/range catalog. This is a Hero-owned config pointer
    under [HERO].

  runtime_root
    Default runtime job artifact root.

  allowed_runtime_roots
    Comma-separated roots under which explicit runtime_root/checkpoint_path
    arguments are allowed. Use /tmp for temporary smoke roots; checked-in
    historical receipts under src/tests/fixtures are not active runtime roots.

  auto_build_exposure_ledger
    When true, target evaluation derives exposure facts from normal runtime
    artifacts. Future DB-backed operation should keep the DB rebuildable from
    those same artifacts.

  max_fact_preview
    Maximum facts returned inline by Lattice inspect/evaluate fact panels.

  max_closure_facts
    Maximum facts returned inline by closure-oriented Lattice inspect/evaluate
    operations.

TOOLS
  hero.lattice.status
  hero.lattice.inspect
  hero.lattice.evaluate
  hero.lattice.compare

MCP SCHEMA HYGIENE
  Tool schemas are a harness-safety gate, not a lattice proof condition.
  Sourced Hero catalog generation validates each inputSchema before emitting
  tools/list JSON: the root must have type=object, and top-level oneOf, anyOf,
  allOf, enum, and not are rejected. Failure messages name the tool,
  schema_path, offending construct, and message. The focused schema smoke covers
  Config, Runtime, Lattice, and Marshal catalogs and protects prior closure
  schema harness failures.

AGENT RUNBOOK
  Lattice Hero is read-only. It does not execute waves and it does not mutate
  runtime evidence.

  status
    Always start here. Report target/split paths, split-policy fingerprint,
    fact counts, warnings, and inferred active identity. The status packet is
    read-only, not target proof, non-dispatchable, not a Runtime executor, and
    reports writes_evidence=false and fact_families_are_not_target_kinds=true.
    It also declares model_selector=false, performance_selector=false,
    policy_gate=false, allocation_decision=false,
    market_readiness_decision=false, and deployment_decision=false.

  list_targets
    Shows every LATTICE_TARGET block compiled from the active target DSL. V0 has
    one active targets file per global config, but that file can contain many
    targets. Protocol-scoped targets may set PROTOCOL_ID; evidence for one
    protocol variant must not satisfy another. The catalog envelope is read-only,
    target_proof=false, dispatchable=false, runtime_executor=false, and
    fact_families_are_not_target_kinds=true.

	  explain_target
	    Explains one compiled proof object without scanning runtime evidence. Use
	    before editing, evaluating, or explaining a target. It includes checkpoint
	    source policy such as latest_satisfying:<target_id>. Model-state plan
    inputs like PLAN_INPUT_MDN_CHECKPOINT and
    PLAN_INPUT_REPRESENTATION_CHECKPOINT are preserved as suggested-wave hints,
    not contract identity or proof evidence. They remain symbolic
    latest_satisfying source-target references until runtime reports prove the
    exact loaded checkpoint paths. Their values do not alter
	    target_spec_fingerprint. Advisory planning knobs such as WAVE_MODE,
	    PLAN_MODE, PLAN_MAX_ATTEMPTS, and MAX_WAVES also do not alter
	    target_spec_fingerprint. Non-blocking LATTICE_WARN clauses
	    remain visible in explanations and evaluations, but they also do not alter
	    target proof identity. Artifact-readiness definitions expose
	    target_surface_kind=evidence_catalog_artifact,
	    dispatchable_target=false, runtime_wave_dispatchable=false, and
	    recommended_operator_action=inspect_evidence_panel before any runtime scan.
    They also emit kind=not_applicable, target_kind_applicable=false, and
    target_kind_effective=none so the internal default enum cannot masquerade as
    a declared TARGET_KIND. Artifact-readiness targets cannot declare
    UPSTREAM_TARGET_ID, LATTICE_DEPENDS, EVALUATED_CHECKPOINT_SOURCE, or
    PLAN_INPUT_* checkpoint hints; artifact lineage comes from fact parent
    digests and proof templates, not target-dependency scheduling. The
    explanation envelope is read-only, target_proof=false, dispatchable=false,
    runtime_executor=false, and
    fact_families_are_not_target_kinds=true.
    target_spec_fingerprint. Explain output includes
    derived_query_rule_vocabulary,
    derived_query_projection_semantics_vocabulary, proof_obligation_vocabulary,
    proof_certificate_digest_policy_vocabulary,
    proof_certificate_digest_policy_summary,
    checkpoint_selection_policy_vocabulary,
    checkpoint_selection_policy_summary,
    plan_advice_scope_policy_vocabulary,
    deficit_vector_planning_summary,
    node_support_scope_policy_summary,
    validation_performance_evidence_policy_summary,
    validation_performance_scope_policy_summary,
    representation_geometry_summary,
    mdn_distribution_calibration_summary,
    mdn_distribution_calibration_diagnostic_summary,
    contract_identity_boundary_vocabulary,
    operational_readiness_v1_scope_vocabulary,
    operational_readiness_v1_gate_vocabulary,
    mathematical_readiness_v1_vocabulary,
    warning_threshold_relation_vocabulary, target_numeric_dimension_vocabulary,
    target_numeric_dimension_summary, and warning_anchor_scope_policy_vocabulary,
    plus the static mathematical
    policy vocabularies for coverage/load algebra, leakage, causal closure,
    DB/cache, evidence abstraction, joins, deficit priority, evidence order,
    support scope, performance scope, geometry, uncertainty, calibration,
    monotonicity, source audit, benchmark budgets, and checkpoint identity. This
    makes proof/query logic, digest and identity
    boundaries, advisory planning boundaries, readiness crosswalks, numeric
    units/bounds, warning trigger semantics, and interval-scope rules available
    before runtime evidence is scanned.
    It also returns warning_scope_previews, a per-warning resolved anchor-range
    preview with resolution status; this is explanation metadata only and does
    not satisfy readiness. A preview status of
    unbounded_all_matching_evidence means the evaluator applies no anchor-range
    filter for that warning kind.

  scan_exposure
    Builds a preview ledger from runtime job artifacts and lattice sidecars.
    The scan is read-only, non-dispatchable, not a target proof, not a Runtime
    executor, and reports fact_families_are_not_target_kinds=true.
    Report warnings verbatim. Fact previews include anchor_domain_health with
    candidate/accepted graph anchors, skip reasons, common/reference key bounds,
    and source-domain warning level. Fact previews also include
    source_key_window and structured source_key_window_audit metadata;
    incomplete, non-numeric, internally non-monotone, row-order-inverting, or
    affine-inconsistent source-key windows produce scan warnings while row-index
    footprints remain the leakage authority. The audit object exposes parsed
    endpoints, order-preservation booleans, and inferred
    key-step/affine-consistency fields, gap-warning counts, and row/source-key
    mismatch counts so agents can inspect the auxiliary source-key coordinate
    map without parsing warning text. scan_exposure also emits
    source_key_map_audit_summary, binding audits to graph-order identity,
    source-cursor identity, and source-receipt parent facts while preserving
    row-index authority. Evaluation and
    planning JSON also expose source_receipt_policy_vocabulary, recording that
    compact source_file_receipts are source-audit metadata only; they do not
    satisfy coverage, prove leakage cleanliness, alter contract identity, or
    replace row-index footprints.
    V2 scan_exposure also emits structured source_receipt_facts and a
    source_receipt_summary. These rows inherit protocol identity from their
    parent exposure fact and are audit/provenance evidence only:
    malformed non-empty compact receipts produce scan warnings, missing receipts
    are counted as audit absence, and row-index intervals remain the
    coverage/leakage authority.
    source_receipt_policy_summary self-checks one row-index coverage/leakage
    authority row, three audit-only receipt rows, no contract identity
    authority, no structured receipt facts in V1, and declared compact/future
    structured receipt fields.
    MDN jobs also expose derived node_exposure previews from per-node
    report fields including routed/active/trained/evaluated row counts, valid
    targets, valid-target opportunity counts, mean NLL, and inherited protocol
    identity.
    node_support_summaries add support-row and unique-node counts, support-row
    incidence counts by exposure use and mutation, ordered support rows,
    aggregate support, weakest-node, Wilson support-bound, and support-balance
    metrics including CV, Gini, and normalized entropy over those MDN facts.
    Support rows include parent exposure fact digests and use flags. Valid-target denominators are
    target-opportunity counts, not plain row counts; routed rows alone are
    visibility, not Wilson denominators.
    These are MDN support facts, not per-node VICReg readiness claims.
    node_support_scope_policy_vocabulary makes that scope boundary explicit:
    MDN rows support MDN-head visibility, not VICReg per-node readiness, and
    future representation-node support must come from NodeLift or
    representation-emitted facts rather than synthetic backfill from MDN rows.
    node_support_scope_policy_summary self-checks the four-row boundary: three
    V1 visibility rows, one deferred future row, no VICReg per-node readiness
    authority, no synthetic backfill, and no runtime executor authority.
    VICReg fact previews may include representation_health with invariance/variance/
    covariance loss components, gradient norm, valid projection rows, adapter
    valid-channel fraction, finite-parameter check, and optional geometry
    metrics such as embedding dimension, effective rank/fraction, min/max
    dimension variance, condition number, and isotropy score. These are
    visibility fields unless a future target explicitly gates on them.
    MTF-JEPA-MAE-VICReg previews use the same compact evidence boundary:
    identity/lineage, finite health, sample/channel support, valid latent rows,
    split JEPA/MAE/TF/VICReg loss means, TF-pair support, VICReg row counts,
    context/EMA diagnostics, and geometry summaries. Raw embeddings, token
    tensors, per-token masks, unbounded histograms, and downstream forecast
    claims are not Lattice facts.

  list_fact_families / scan_facts / fact_summary / fact_lineage / fact_preview
    Inspect the generic fact catalog without evaluating targets. Fact families
    are not TARGET_KIND values. These tools report read_only=true,
    target_proof=false, dispatchable=false, runtime_executor=false,
    writes_evidence=false, fact_families_are_not_target_kinds=true, and
    no model, performance, policy-gate, allocation, market-readiness, or
    deployment decision authority at the top level. Use them for source
    analytics, target transform,
    forecast baseline/eval, observer belief, allocation engine, and replay
    environment evidence before deciding whether a narrow artifact_readiness
    target is appropriate. Their catalog summaries expose zero-count
    decision-authority fields for quality,
    performance, checkpoint selection, allocation, execution, market/deploy,
    policy gates, target dependencies, Runtime waves, Marshal reachability,
    checkpoint sources, and plan checkpoint inputs; decision_authority_clean=true
    means the catalog remains evidence only.
    Registry and catalog-summary rows also expose
    fact_identity_contract. This is the shared runtime evidence identity
    envelope: schema/fact_type/digest, parent exposure digest when applicable,
    protocol/contract/graph/source-cursor/split/component/job-wave identity,
    row-index anchor/completed intervals, lineage digest fields, and support
    fields. The contract explicitly keeps row-index intervals authoritative,
    source-key windows audit-only, and target-kind, Runtime-wave, Marshal
    reachability, and policy-gate authority false.
    scan_facts, fact_summary, fact_lineage, and fact_preview include
    fact_integrity_summary, a top-level rollup of declared, bound, unresolved,
    identity-mismatch, and digest-mismatch relation counts plus affected
    families and issue codes. fact_lineage additionally exposes selected
    runtime-index relation/key/digest rows as audit-only lineage witnesses;
    cache rows are never used for target satisfaction. fact_preview returns
    concrete rows for one family by digest, digest prefix, or fact index, plus
    matching lineage rows. Preview rows are audit-only,
    facts_used_for_target_satisfaction=false, and checkpoint_selected=false.
    Each preview row also includes identity_envelope, a normalized typed
    Lattice catalog projection of the shared fact_identity_contract. Hero only
    serializes this projection. It includes family, digest, active identity,
    row-index ranges, parent digests, support counters when present, and
    no-proof/no-dispatch/no-selection authority flags.
    Artifact-readiness proof rows also expose fact_preview_hint, and blocked
    artifact plan_basis rows aggregate fact_preview_hints so operators can jump
    from a failed proof to the concrete catalog row. These hints are
    inspection-only and do not affect target status, certificate digest,
    checkpoint selection, or dispatch.
    Parked replay_environment rows are audit evidence only when explicitly
    inspected. They are not active artifact-readiness proof templates, not
    derived by default scans, and not Runtime execution, allocation, or
    market-readiness signals.
    Fact-family registry and summary rows expose artifact_readiness_proof_kind
    and artifact_readiness_proof_claim for proofable catalog families, and null
    values for warning/summary-only families. Non-proofable rows also expose
    artifact_readiness_target_promotion_blocked=true plus a concrete reason such
    as warning_summary_only, leakage_visibility_only, or support_visibility_only.
    A fact family can become artifact_readiness only through an explicit
    proof template. source_analytics remains warning/summary evidence and
    cannot be promoted by declaring a new PROOF_KIND.
    LATTICE_POLICY_GATE declarations are future-policy reservations only.
    ENABLED=false gates are parsed for review and fingerprinted only for
    forecast_quality_acceptance and allocation_acceptance reservations bound to
    the matching artifact_readiness proof target; they are ignored by target
    satisfaction, plan readiness, suggested waves, and target_spec_fingerprint.
    performance_acceptance, market_readiness, and deployment_readiness remain
    unsupported fail-closed future decision surfaces.
    If POLICY_FINGERPRINT is supplied it must match the canonical reserved
    policy declaration digest. ENABLED=true fails closed until policy authority,
    metric definitions, baseline definitions, thresholds, uncertainty policy
    and model, support minimums, selector split, tie policy, anti-leakage
    policy, negative tests, calibration requirements, holdout declaration, and
    threshold-selection audit are explicit.
    list_targets, explain_target, evaluate_target, target_deficit, and
    evaluate_targets expose policy_gate_reservations plus
    policy_gate_reservation_summary so clients can inspect future gates while
    seeing canonical policy-fingerprint verification, required policy inputs,
    missing input lists, policy-input contract completeness, and zero
    decision-policy, target-status, target-fingerprint, proof-certificate,
    runtime, allocation,
    market-readiness, and deployment authority.

  evaluate_target
    Proves whether one target is satisfied by the runtime evidence. For
    exposure-backed targets, returns exposure_summaries with unique coverage,
    repeated cursor-epoch exposure load, and optimizer-step density. These
    summaries do not change status by themselves. Validation evaluation targets
    use evaluation_metric coverage from run-mode jobs with no component mutation
    and zero optimizer steps; they must bind exactly to the evaluated checkpoint
    input edges and must not write a new checkpoint. When a target declares
    EVALUATED_CHECKPOINT_SOURCE, evaluation also proves the run loaded the exact
    MDN checkpoint selected by that source target, plus the matching
    representation checkpoint lineage. LATTICE_WARN clauses return typed
    non-blocking warning_results; warnings projects those typed envelopes for
    Marshal and other agents, while warning_messages preserves the ordered
    projection of triggered warning_results messages. The response envelope marks target_proof=true and
    target_proof_engine=lattice_target_evaluator while still declaring
    read_only=true, dispatchable=false, runtime_executor=false,
    writes_evidence=false, and fact_families_are_not_target_kinds=true.
    Artifact-readiness evaluations additionally include
    fact_integrity_summary scoped to SUBJECT_FACT_FAMILY. This is catalog
    context only: unresolved, identity-mismatched, or digest-mismatched
    relation counts explain artifact proof issues but do not create a separate
    scheduler, target dependency, executor, or policy gate. Proof deficits include
    related_fact_integrity_issue_codes when an artifact proof issue matches a
    concrete catalog issue row, for example
    mdn:baseline_fact_digest_not_found.
    Missing warning measurements are reported as unavailable with their
    configured threshold while remaining non-blocking.
    Each warning result carries warning_family, source=lattice,
    component=lattice_target, blocking=false,
    readiness_effect=non_blocking_warning_only, evidence_digest,
    machine_reason_code, human_explanation, suggested_inspection_panel,
    target_ids_observed_against, and evidence_basis so agents can distinguish
    exposure_load_summary, source_analytics_facts, forecast_baseline_facts,
    forecast_eval_facts, observer_belief_facts, allocation_engine_facts,
    filtered_node_support_summary, representation_health_facts, and
    anchor_domain_facts measurements.
    exposure_summary_available and node_support_summary_available mark which
    summary envelope is a real warning basis rather than an empty placeholder.
    Any LATTICE_WARN kind may use SPLIT or explicit ANCHOR_INDEX_BEGIN/END.
    Warning measurements are scoped to that warning interval, defaulting to the
    target range. If trusted completed coverage is unavailable, warning overlap
    can use anchor-range visibility without making that evidence satisfy
    readiness coverage. Each warning_result exposes the resolved interval as
    warning_anchor_range; explain_target exposes the same pre-evaluation scope
    as warning_scope_previews[].resolved_warning_anchor_range; and
    warning_anchor_scope_policy_vocabulary documents the visibility-only
    fallback for both surfaces. Node-support warnings derive a warning-range
    support matrix before applying USE/EFFECT filters, while the proof
    certificate keeps its target-range node_support_summaries.
    Warning results expose threshold_direction, threshold_triggered, and
    threshold_relation next to threshold, so clients do not have to parse status
    strings or diagnostic messages to know the comparison operator or trigger
    state. warning_threshold_relation_vocabulary exposes the allowed relation
    values with their trigger and measurement-availability semantics.
    warning_summary aggregates warning-result count, triggered-warning count,
    unavailable-warning count, clear measured warnings, blocking and
    non-blocking warning counts, all_warnings_non_blocking, the compatibility
    warning_count alias, and threshold-relation counts for clients that only
    need aggregate warning state.
    Each result also includes proof_certificate, a machine-readable proof object
    containing a certificate_digest, target/split fingerprints, identity,
    dependency, artifact, idempotent coverage, closure, and leakage checks.
    Artifact-readiness rows in proof_certificate.artifacts[] expose explicit
    false authority flags for quality/performance, checkpoint selection,
    allocation/execution, market/deployment, policy gates, target dependencies,
    Runtime waves, Marshal reachability, checkpoint sources, plan checkpoint
    inputs, model-state mutation, raw-potential tradable-return claims, and
    replay execution. They also expose fact_schema, fact_type,
    fact_identity_contract_id, fact_identity_contract_bound,
    fact_identity_envelope_complete, row_index_interval_authority, and
    source_key_window_audit_only so clients can see that the artifact proof is
    bound to the generic fact identity contract. proof_template_bound and
    proof_template_claim show that the row's proof_kind is bound to the
    registered artifact proof template for its fact family, not just to
    arbitrary fact existence. If an
    identity-matched artifact fact exists but fails, the failed evaluation keeps
    the first matching artifact row with passed=false, the drift flags, and the
    issue list. Deficits are derived from that row with artifact-specific keys
    such as artifact:forecast_eval_authority instead of a generic certificate
    failure. Certificate
    digests canonicalize dependency proofs and other set-like summaries before
    hashing. Coverage proof records contributing intervals, contributing fact
    digests, contributing fact witnesses, merged covered intervals, and missing
    complement intervals. The certificate check recomputes the merged
    idempotent union and missing complement, so scalar totals alone are not
    enough for a valid proof. It also checks additive load counts against the
    contributing interval list before union, recomputes witness digests and
    intervals, and binds mutating coverage fact digests back to closure causal
    exposures. Non-mutating evaluation_metric coverage witnesses are also bound
    exactly to the MDN and representation input checkpoint edges declared by a
    satisfied EVALUATED_CHECKPOINT_SOURCE dependency, must not carry extra
    checkpoint input edges, and must not carry an output checkpoint edge.
    Coverage deficits also include the missing intervals.
    Leakage proof records the protected split, undilated split interval,
    Hx/Hf-dilated protected interval, and left/right dilation widths.
    Leakage failures include overlap witnesses with fact digest, forbidden use,
    source footprint, and intersection interval. leakage_rule_vocabulary exposes
    protected_split_dilation_intersection as temporal morphological dilation
    over complete checkpoint closure with labeled causal-exposure witnesses.
    leakage_rule_summary self-checks the single V1 rule, complete-closure
    requirement, protected-range/base containment, empty-intersection predicate,
    and causal witness basis.
    Node-MDN certificates include
    derived node_support_summaries when inherited MDN node facts are available.
    proof_certificate_digest_policy_vocabulary exposes the digest boundary:
    target/split identity, identity, dependency, coverage/load, closure,
    leakage, checkpoint-preview audit fields, and MDN node-support summaries
    are canonical proof content; the digest value itself, warnings, deficits,
    plan advice, evidence-order projections, and policy vocabularies are not.
    proof_certificate_digest_policy_summary counts the 12 policy rows, 9 hashed
    proof surfaces, 3 excluded report/policy surfaces, zero advisory digest
    overlap, and zero visibility-only status authority.
    proof_certificate_check reports local self-consistency of the certificate
    digest, schema, target fingerprint presence, dependency kind/status
    vocabulary, split-policy identity for concrete named-split facts, and proof
    arithmetic. Evaluation filtering rejects concrete named-split exposure facts
    that omit split-policy identity while a split policy is active; historical
    unknown-split facts remain admissible. Unsatisfied targets may still pass
    this check when the
    certificate is a well-formed non-claiming envelope; use
    status, reasons, and deficits for the target failure. A malformed certificate
    on a would-be satisfied target fails closed as
    certificate:proof_certificate_check. The check covers
    upstream dependency non-binding semantics, satisfied
    checkpoint-source path completeness, required identity field presence,
    identity match booleans, exact non-vacuous checkpoint
    dependency bindings, coverage
    duplicate dependency rejection, use/fraction dimensions, positive coverage requirement thresholds,
    non-vacuous coverage target ranges, interval arithmetic, checked-closure checkpoint identity, non-vacuous complete closure facts, closure counts,
    causal output-checkpoint presence, causal checkpoint edge-label
    presence/uniqueness, root-reachable causal output closure, causal input-edge
    producer/unresolved resolution and exclusivity, causal checkpoint self-loop/cycle/root-cycle rejection,
    coverage/load mutation-filter agreement, finite load/effort/support
    measures, load component-scope vocabulary, target-component-local coverage load scope,
    duplicate coverage obligation rejection,
    target-component assembly identity in mutated coverage causal support,
    mutated coverage causal-closure support and contributing-interval
    multiplicity, runtime evaluation coverage as non-mutating evidence outside
    checkpoint closure,
    unchecked-closure and unchecked-leakage non-claiming semantics, causal
    identity envelope/component-assembly/job-wave identity/completed-range presence,
    checked-closure root checkpoint producer assembly identity, non-vacuous
    leakage base range, protected split dilation, closure incompleteness witness presence/uniqueness/reachability,
    named-split leakage proof
    split-policy identity, leakage
    forbidden-use membership, leakage proof complete-closure backing, leakage
    witness closure membership, leakage witness job/wave identity, leakage
    witness causal-field consistency, leakage witness set recomputation from
    causal closure overlaps, leakage witness mutation requirements, non-empty leakage
    intersections, duplicate leakage overlap witness rejection, valid-target uncertainty support totals, valid-target
    no-trials uncertainty non-claiming, Wilson bounds, MDN-only node-support
    scope, inherited causal MDN exposure use/mutation/split/assembly backing
    for mutating node support, non-mutating validation/evaluation node support
    as row-parent exposure evidence, duplicate node-support summary rejection,
    non-empty node-support summaries,
    finite-fraction claim/non-claim semantics, and node-support summary
    schema/aggregate and weakest-node arithmetic/non-claiming/identity/mean/
    support-row identity/order/fraction/use-incidence/provenance and
    recomputation/balance-metric/row-count bounds. For leakage, the check
    recomputes protected = [base.begin - left, base.end + right) before trusting
    witness intersections.
    Target satisfaction is monotone only under clean evidence growth; forbidden
    or protected-footprint evidence can still turn a ready target into
    exposure_failed.
    Results also include evidence_order_vector, a Pareto-order basis over
    separate identity, coverage, load, closure, leakage, node-support
    confidence, node-support imbalance, source-key audit issue counts,
    unresolved-lineage count, deficit-count, warning-result count,
    triggered-warning count, and unavailable-warning count dimensions.
    Selection-signal leakage excludes a checkpoint before dominance is
    considered.
    exposure_measure_algebra_vocabulary exposes the shared coverage/load
    algebra semantics: unique coverage is idempotent interval union, repeated
    load is additive interval measure.
    exposure_measure_algebra_summary self-checks that there are exactly two
    measures, one idempotent coverage measure, one additive load measure, no
    dual-role measure, and distinct coverage/load units.
    source_key_coordinate_policy_vocabulary records that row-index intervals
    are authoritative for coverage/leakage and source-key windows are audit-only
    order-preserving/affine/gap map checks.
    source_key_coordinate_policy_summary self-checks exactly one row-index
    coverage/leakage authority row, four audit-only source-key rows, declared
    order-preserving/affine/gap fields, and no source-key audit row with
    coverage or leakage authority.
    warning_count remains the compatibility alias for triggered warnings. It is
    projected from warning_summary. The vector is not a scalar lattice score, and
    dimensions can remain incomparable. Internal callers can use
    compare_lattice_evidence_order_vectors for the explicit
    dominance/equivalence/incomparability/selector-leaked relation; Hero JSON
    includes the same relation vocabulary, dimension-order polarity, and
	    dimension_vocabulary. hero.lattice.compare evaluates two targets
	    with one scan and returns both vectors, per-dimension dominance rows,
	    participation/exclusion reasons, and the final partial-order relation
	    with explicit false authority flags for checkpoint selection, model
	    selection, quality acceptance, policy gates, allocation, market readiness,
	    scalar scores, and deployment decisions.
	    beside the vector for agent reporting. The vocabulary comes from the same C++
	    source as the comparator. checkpoint_selection_policy_vocabulary records
	    that latest_satisfying is a deterministic readiness selector, not a
    best-model, Pareto, performance, deployment, or scalar-score selector.
    checkpoint_selection_policy_summary records the compact self-check for that
    policy: 4 rows, 3 deterministic readiness selectors, exact runtime binding
    rows for evaluated/model-state inputs, and zero performance, Pareto,
    identity, or executor authority.
    source as the comparator. Warning results expose threshold_triggered and
    measurement_available; triggered-warning and unavailable-warning dimensions
    are derived from those structured bits instead of status/message wording.
    Repeated cursor-load only strengthens the vector as clean load;
    if it comes with more warnings, the relation remains incomparable.
    Unsatisfied results include deficits, a compact list of missing or
    contradicted proof dimensions. Each deficit carries a stable
    key=kind:dimension plus deterministic priority and priority_class fields for
    planning and indexing. Missing active contract/component/graph/source
    identity inputs and stale runtime evidence with mismatched
    contract/component/graph/source identity surface as identity:* deficits.
    Scalar readiness failures such as finite loss, optimizer effort, valid-target fraction, and
    node-head counts surface as metric:* deficits. Missing manifests, reports,
    checkpoint files, exposure
    ledgers, closure facts, active exposure facts, target-component-local
    exposure facts, producer exposure facts, split policies, candidate state files, and
    non-completed job status surface as artifact:* deficits.
    Cyclic target dependency graphs surface as dependency:target_cycle.
